title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
The expectation (or mean) of a random variable (X) is a measure of the central tendency of the distribution of (X). For a continuous random variable (X), the expectation is given by the integral of the value of (X) with its probability density function (PDF) (f_X(x)):
\[
\mu = E[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x f_X(x) dx
\]
Example: Consider a continuous random variable (X) representing the height of people in a city. The expectation (E[X]) is the average height of all people in that city.

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
The expectation (or mean) of a random variable (X) is a measure of the central tendency of the distribution of (X). For a continuous random variable (X), the expectation is given by the integral of the value of (X) with its probability density function (PDF) (f_X(x)):
\[
\mu = E[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x f_X(x) dx
\]
Example: Consider a continuous random variable (X) representing the height of people in a city. The expectation (E[X]) is the average height of all people in that city.

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
Variance
The variance of a random variable (X) is a measure of the dispersion or spread of the distribution of (X) around its mean. It is given by:
\[
\text{Var}(X) = E\left[(X - E[X])^2\right] = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2
\]
The square root of the variance is called the standard deviation, denoted by sigma
\[
\sigma = \sqrt{\text{Var}(X)} = \sqrt{E\left[(X - E[X])^2\right]} = \sqrt{E[X^2] - (E[X])^2}
\]
Example: Continuing with the height example, the variance tells us how much the heights of people in the city vary around the average height. A higher variance means more variation in heights.

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
Conditional Expectation
The conditional expectation of (X), given that another random variable (Y) equals (y), is the expected value of (X) when (Y = y). It is given by:
\[
E[X | Y = y] = \int{-\infty}^{\infty} x f{X|Y}(x|y) , dx
\]
Example: If (X) is the height of people and (Y) is their age, (E[X | Y = y]) is the average height of people who are (y) years old.

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
Covariance
The covariance between two random variables (X) and (Y) is a measure of the linear relationship between them. It is given by:
\[
\text{Cov}(X, Y) = E[(X - E[X])(Y - E[Y])] = E[XY] - E[X]E[Y]
\]
Example: If (X) is the height of people and (Y) is their weight, the covariance tells us how changes in height are related to changes in weight.

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
Correlation
The correlation between two random variables (X) and (Y) is the normalization of the covariance by the product of their standard deviations. It is represented by the Greek letter ():
\[
\rho(X, Y) = \frac{\text{Cov}(X, Y)}{\sqrt{\text{Var}(X) \text{Var}(Y)}}
\]
Example: Continuing with height and weight, the correlation coefficient ((X, Y)) tells us how strongly height and weight are related, ranging from -1 (perfect negative correlation) to 1 (perfect positive correlation).

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
Example: Uniform Distribution
If (X) follows a uniform distribution on the interval ([a, b]), the PDF (f_X(x)) is:
\[
f_X(x) = \frac{1}{b - a}
\]
The expectation (E[X]) is given by:
\[
E[X] = \int_a^b x f_X(x) , dx = \int_a^b \frac{x}{b - a} , dx = \left. \frac{x^2}{2(b - a)} \right|_a^b = \frac{a + b}{2}
\]
Example: If (X) represents the time it takes for a bus to arrive, uniformly distributed between 0 and 20 minutes, the expected waiting time (E[X]) is 10 minutes.

title: Properties of Random Variables
text:
## Expectation (Mean)
The expectation (or mean) of a random variable \(X\) is a measure of the central tendency of the distribution of \(X\). For a continuous random variable \(X\), the expectation is given by the integral of the value of \(X\) with its probability density function (PDF) \(f_X(x)\):
\[
\mu = E[X] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x f_X(x) \, dx
\]
**Example**: Consider a continuous random variable \(X\) representing the height of people in a city. The expectation \(E[X]\) is the average height of all people in that city.
## Variance
The variance of a random variable \(X\) is a measure of the dispersion or spread of the distribution of \(X\) around its mean. It is given by:
\[
\text{Var}(X) = E\left[(X - E[X])^2\right] = E[X^2] - (E[X])^2
\]
The square root of the variance is called the standard deviation, denoted by \(\sigma\):
\[
\sigma = \sqrt{\text{Var}(X)} = \sqrt{E\left[(X - E[X])^2\right]} = \sqrt{E[X^2] - (E[X])^2}
\]
**Example**: Continuing with the height example, the variance tells us how much the heights of people in the city vary around the average height. A higher variance means more variation in heights.
## Conditional Expectation
The conditional expectation of \(X\), given that another random variable \(Y\) equals \(y\), is the expected value of \(X\) when \(Y = y\). It is given by:
\[
E[X | Y = y] = \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x f_{X|Y}(x|y) \, dx
\]
**Example**: If \(X\) is the height of people and \(Y\) is their age, \(E[X | Y = y]\) is the average height of people who are \(y\) years old.
## Covariance
The covariance between two random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) is a measure of the linear relationship between them. It is given by:
\[
\text{Cov}(X, Y) = E[(X - E[X])(Y - E[Y])] = E[XY] - E[X]E[Y]
\]
**Example**: If \(X\) is the height of people and \(Y\) is their weight, the covariance tells us how changes in height are related to changes in weight.
## Correlation
The correlation between two random variables \(X\) and \(Y\) is the normalization of the covariance by the product of their standard deviations. It is represented by the Greek letter \(\rho\):
\[
\rho(X, Y) = \frac{\text{Cov}(X, Y)}{\sqrt{\text{Var}(X) \text{Var}(Y)}}
\]
**Example**: Continuing with height and weight, the correlation coefficient \(\rho(X, Y)\) tells us how strongly height and weight are related, ranging from -1 (perfect negative correlation) to 1 (perfect positive correlation).
## Example: Uniform Distribution
If \(X\) follows a uniform distribution on the interval \([a, b]\), the PDF \(f_X(x)\) is:
\[
f_X(x) = \frac{1}{b - a}
\]
The expectation \(E[X]\) is given by:
\[
E[X] = \int_a^b x f_X(x) \, dx = \int_a^b \frac{x}{b - a} \, dx = \left. \frac{x^2}{2(b - a)} \right|_a^b = \frac{a + b}{2}
\]
**Example**: If \(X\) represents the time it takes for a bus to arrive, uniformly distributed between 0 and 20 minutes, the expected waiting time \(E[X]\) is 10 minutes.
